#1
library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.4.4
library(tidyr)
## Warning: package 'tidyr' was built under R version 3.4.4
x = replicate(1000, rnorm(30, mean = 50, sd = 10))

myrangex <- function(x) {max(x) - min(x)}
Range <- apply(x, 2, myrangex)
Median <- apply(x, 2, median)
Mean <- apply(x, 2, mean)
SD <- apply(x, 2, sd)
Q3 <- apply(x, 2, quantile)
Q3 <- Q3[4, 1:1000]
Population <- "Normal"

my_data_frame_x <- data.frame(Median, SD, Range, Q3, Population)

data_long_x <- gather(my_data_frame_x, condition, measurement, Median, SD, Range, Q3)

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(data = data_long_x, aes(y = measurement, fill = condition)) +
  xlab("Condition") + ylab("Value") + ggtitle("Spread of Summary Statistics from a Normal Distribution") +
  facet_wrap(~condition)

#2

y = replicate(1000, runif(30, min = 10, max = 90))

myrangey <- function(y) {max(y) - min(y)}
Range <- apply(y, 2, myrangey)
Median <- apply(y, 2, median)
Mean <- apply(y, 2, mean)
SD <- apply(y, 2, sd)
my_quantile <- apply(y, 2, quantile)
Q3 <- my_quantile[4, 1:1000]
Population <- "Uniform"

my_data_frame_y <- data.frame(Median, SD, Range, Q3, Population)

data_long_y <- gather(my_data_frame_y, condition, measurement, Median, SD, Range, Q3)

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(data = data_long_y, aes(y = measurement, fill = condition)) +
  xlab("Condition") + ylab("Value") + ggtitle("Spread of Summary Statistics from a Uniform Distribution") +
  facet_wrap(~condition)

#3

z = replicate(1000, rexp(30, rate = .02))

myrangez <- function(z) {max(z) - min(z)}
Range <- apply(z, 2, myrangey)
Median <- apply(z, 2, median)
Mean <- apply(z, 2, mean)
SD <- apply(z, 2, sd)
my_quantile <- apply(z, 2, quantile)
Q3 <- my_quantile[4, 1:1000]
Population <- "Exponential"

my_data_frame_z <- data.frame(Median, SD, Range, Q3, Population)

data_long_z <- gather(my_data_frame_z, condition, measurement, Median, SD, Range, Q3)

ggplot() + geom_boxplot(data = data_long_z, aes(y = measurement, fill = condition)) +
  xlab("Condition") + ylab("Value") + ggtitle("Spread of Summary Statistics from an Exponential Distribution") +
  facet_wrap(~condition)

#4
my_data_long_total <- rbind(data_long_x, data_long_y, data_long_z)

ggplot() + geom_histogram(data = my_data_long_total, aes(x = measurement, fill = Population)) +
  xlab("Condition") + ylab("Value") + ggtitle("Spread of Summary Statistics") + facet_wrap(~condition, nrow = 2)

#5
#These sampling distributions are much more descriptive than just the mean. From these sampling statistics we learn more about the data such as the spread and variability which in the long run, can reveal more to observers. 

#These sampling distributions are sensitive to their population distributions. We can see that summary statistics calculated from an Exponential Distribution are lower than that of a Normal Distribution.
